Isn’t it funny how challenging it is to take our own advice?

I’ve been advising clients to take time to build their communities for YEARS now, but it wasn’t until two years ago that I started to really do it for myself. (You know the saying... The cobbler’s kids have no shoes 🙈)

And guess what? Since I started creating content for myself, I’ve (pinch me) built a brand new business vertical from scratch.

In 2019, brand partnerships didn’t exist for me. In 2022, I pass over 6 figures in brand deals and ads revenue.

I don’t love to write, but I certainly love to talk. And I love to teach people how to do cool things. I’ve discovered that brands need real people to ‘humanize’ their products and services, and they’re willing to pay for it. You don’t need to be an ‘influencer’ or a huge creator, either. You just need to be a passionate communicator that people and brands trust.

I’m very proud of my partnerships with @AdobeExpress, @Convertkit, @Teachable,  @Synthesiaio, and many others (36 to be exact). 

Plus, it’s a lot of fun!

So, take this as an encouraging reminder from me to invest time in yourself, starting now. Believe in your ability to uniquely communicate. Pair something you love with something others need, and the money will follow.

I want to make sure @Sync is on your radar 📡 Popular cloud storage solutions (Google, Dropbox, OneDrive) actually aren’t the best when it comes to:

· Privacy
· Price
· Unlimited storage

Finally, it’s more affordable.

This is exactly how we’re repurposing content in 2023 🧱 It's taken time and lots of tweaks, but this graphic illustrates how one piece long-form content becomes at least four others!

Step 1 • It starts with a podcast episode. @thelaurenmoore and I discuss a topic we're both interested in. We either learn from guest expert or research something to share with our listener. Without this recording slot on our busy schedules, we'd never otherwise make time for it.

Step 2 • @thelaurenmoore actually finishes an outline for a blog post by the time we finish recording. We use AI copywriting tools to help complete that blog post before sharing it with the world.

Step 3 • I then take that post and turn it into a YouTube video script. Starting from an existing blog post cuts my research and writing time in half.

Step 4 • I'm pretty familiar with the topic by now, so it's easy to create an Instagram graphic (like this one), a reel, or a carousel—or all of the above!

Step 5 • The final step is creating Pinterest pins! I use branded templates I've created for myself in @adobeexpress. This only takes a few minutes, but can often drive hundreds (or thousands) of extra views to our content.

Feel free to be strongly inspired by this workflow for your own content! I hope this is helpful.

And don’t miss @thelaurenmoore and I discussing our content repurposing workflow in more detail tomorrow at 4pm ET for the live recording of our podcast Brand Therapy: philp.al/176 (link in bio!)

Do you repurpose your content? How is your process similar or different? Do share! ⬇️

My phil-osophy (get it?) is simple: Be selfish with your content. Make sure there’s more in its creation for YOU than anyone else.

Selfish content doesn’t mean that it lacks value. You still need to show expertise. But, ideally, selfish content is something that makes you burst with pride and excitement, to the point where you don’t need likes and comments for validation.

Maybe creating it required some research or brainstorming you wouldn’t have otherwise made time for.

Another example: After recording 175 episodes of our podcast Brand Therapy, we realized that we needed a break to get re-inspired.

We were proud of our podcast (no question there), but it wasn’t something that we wanted to listen to ourselves. Creating it felt like a chore.

After a longer-than-intended break, we are back, reinvigorated, and beyond excited to bring Brand Therapy back. We have a better content repurposing plan in place (yesterday’s post) so our conversations fuel everywhere else we show up. 

Instead of being pigeon-holed by self-imposed structural “rules,” we’re dropping all formats and instead following our instincts with each episode.

Make the content you want to consume.

WE’VE GOT A COMMUNICATION PROBLEM 📣 I, like many of you, get hundreds of emails per day. 

Many of those emails require replies. I want to be thoughtful with my reply, but I also don't have the time to spend 30-60 minutes on a response.

I've noticed more and more people use email as a dumping ground for ideas, open-ended questions, and long discussions. 

There's nothing wrong with any of those things, but email is not the appropriate medium.

I once read a Fast Company article about how Barack Obama trained his White House staff to write emails that were conducive for quick replies. He asked that everyone compose emails so that he could reply with, "Yes," "No," or "Let's discuss."

The next time you write an email, write it so you can get a quick reply. Rephrase your questions so that someone can respond with yes or no. You'll move the ball along faster, and you'll also make it easier for the other person.

BIG CHANGES IN MOTION! 🏆In fact, some of the biggest in our company's 12-year history.

Here are just a few:

• We've completely restructured our service cadence this year, and it's been such a success so far. Instead of doing 25+ branding/website projects simultaneously, we're working on 1-2 projects simultaneously with much more focus and a quicker turnaround. This change has transformed a project length from 4+ months to 3-6 weeks, and clients now reserve a designated project start and end time well into the future.

• Every client is on Slack! We've been using it with most clients for a while, but some people resisted getting out of email. With all these new changes, we now require clients to get on Slack because it saves account management time, fosters collaboration, reduces inbox volume and helps us stay connected via audio notes instead of meetings.

• We're documenting our systems and processes with SOPs! To date, every system and process has been in @thelaurenmoore and my heads, which isn't good! In January, we hired Jess to shadow us and document every part of our business operations (from how we do mood boards to how we write website copy) so we can start giving our hats to future team members.

• We're shaping the business around what we love to do! When you run your own business, you often get stuck doing what you 'have' to do, not what you LOVE to do. We’re now working with a developer to help lay the groundwork for sites, and Jess will soon be the day-to-day contact for clients. Lauren and I will still be deeply involved, but we'll work within our strengths (mine = teaching, coaching, Lauren = writing, strategy) to deliver our clients the best results.

It’s Friday and this is where we’re at 🤪 but if you’re feeling more productive than me, here are 3 fun ways to brainstorm:

1. Rapid ideation

Set a timer and write out as many ideas as possible within a time limit. You're aiming for quantity rather than quality. Anything goes. 

2. Round robin

Grab a group of people and ask everyone to contribute one idea. Wait for everyone to share their idea before discussing, elaborating, criticizing, or sharing a second idea. 

3. Opposite day

Brainstorm ideas that are the opposite of what you aim to create. It will help you better articulate what you do want from the exercise.

Have a great weekend!

I’m demonstrating 5 ChatGPT prompt types to try for your small business—including copy-and-paste examples, below:

✍🏼 1. FILL IN THE BLANK PROMPT IDEAS

A structured approach, providing context and explicit information to guide ChatGPT toward generating the most relevant recommendations.

→ “Provide 20 examples of open-ended questions to include in a customer survey for [company type]”

→ “Here is a sales email I have written [insert the email or describe the email]. Come up with a subject line that’s [adjective] and [adjective].”

💬 2. OPEN-ENDED PROMPT IDEAS

Explore thoughts and creativity without limitations—great for brainstorming or thinking outside the box.

→ “Can you suggest some unique and eye-catching images that could grab the attention of my target audience?”

→ “How can I use color psychology to create a brand that resonates with my target audience and drives conversions?”

📦 3. INSTRUCTIONAL PROMPT IDEAS

Carefully crafting clear instructions that specify the desired task, context, and outcome—perfect for generating code and transcriptions.

→ “What are the steps to prepare for my personal brand photo shoot?”

→ “What steps should I follow to do effective cold outreach?”

🪧 4. SCENARIO PROMPT IDEAS

Provide a contextual scenario to ChatGPT, which it will reply with a proposed solution.

→ “What would you do if a customer complained about [issue]?”

→ Imagine you’re pitching an investor for a new mobile app that helps people save money on hotel bookings. Explain the problem the app solves and the target audience for the app.

👍 5. FEEDBACK PROMPT IDEAS

Get feedback or suggestions on a product, service, or idea. If you want feedback on something specific, you’re best to paste it directly into ChatGPT.

→ “I need a response to a customer who has provided feedback on our product/service and has some suggestions for improvement. Can you write a professional reply?”

→ “Brand statement: [paste]
Give me feedback on my brand statement by evaluating its clarity, conciseness, and overall effectiveness.”
